AIPET X -- Alembic database migrations
=======================================

Run from the repository root:

    venv/bin/alembic <command>

Common commands:

    venv/bin/alembic current       # show the current revision
    venv/bin/alembic history       # list all revisions
    venv/bin/alembic upgrade head  # apply pending migrations
    venv/bin/alembic downgrade -1  # roll one revision back
    venv/bin/alembic revision --autogenerate -m "<description>"
                                   # create a new migration from
                                   # model changes

Two roles, two URLs (PLB-1 convention)
--------------------------------------
The app and the migrations connect to PostgreSQL with different roles
so the application user cannot create or drop databases.

* aipet_user (LOGIN, no CREATEDB)
    DATABASE_URL=postgresql://aipet_user:aipet_password@localhost:5433/aipet_db
    Used by the running Flask app at runtime.

* aipet_admin (LOGIN, CREATEDB; inherits from aipet_user)
    ALEMBIC_DATABASE_URL=postgresql://aipet_admin:aipet_admin_password@localhost:5433/aipet_db
    Used by alembic for upgrade / downgrade / stamp / autogenerate
    and for creating throwaway test databases.

env.py reads ALEMBIC_DATABASE_URL first and falls back to
DATABASE_URL. Set ALEMBIC_DATABASE_URL in .env (or in your shell)
before running any migration command.

The placeholder password aipet_admin_password is for the development
environment only. Production must replace it with a value from secrets
management (Vault / AWS Secrets Manager / 1Password / ...) and remove
it from .env before deployment.

Authoring a migration
---------------------
1. Edit a model under dashboard/backend/<module>/models.py.
2. Run:
       venv/bin/alembic revision --autogenerate -m "describe what changed"
3. READ THE GENERATED FILE LINE-BY-LINE. Autogenerate is not perfect:
   * Indexes may be missed (especially partial / functional indexes).
   * Server-side defaults that match a model default may be omitted.
   * Sequences, triggers and stored functions are NEVER autogenerated.
   * Custom check constraints often need manual addition.
4. If anything is missing, edit the generated file and add op.execute()
   blocks or explicit op.create_index() calls. Mirror every addition
   in downgrade().
5. Test forward and back on a throwaway DB before committing:
       PGPASSWORD=aipet_admin_password psql -h localhost -p 5433 \
         -U aipet_admin -d postgres \
         -c "DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS aipet_migration_check;"
       PGPASSWORD=aipet_admin_password psql -h localhost -p 5433 \
         -U aipet_admin -d postgres \
         -c "CREATE DATABASE aipet_migration_check OWNER aipet_user;"
       ALEMBIC_DATABASE_URL=postgresql://aipet_admin:aipet_admin_password@localhost:5433/aipet_migration_check \
         venv/bin/alembic upgrade head
       ALEMBIC_DATABASE_URL=... venv/bin/alembic downgrade base
       ALEMBIC_DATABASE_URL=... venv/bin/alembic upgrade head
6. Commit only after the round-trip succeeds.

Critical: backup before applying in any non-dev environment.
See docs/runbooks/backup-and-restore.md.
